sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE MOVE TO THE TOP AFTER AN INNINGS WIN.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons scored a four-wicket haul of 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by 39 runs in two days to take the lead in the county championship.

Their position at the top may be short-lived, however, as championship rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey are all close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in a rain-affected match against Nottinghamshire.

After bowling Somerset for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire added 94 runs in their first innings before being bowled out for 296, with England bowler Andy Caddick scoring three 83s.
Somerset started their second innings with a solid 213-point lead until Simmons stepped in and dropped them 174 points.
However, Essex look certain to regain their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a strong grip in their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, who was considered surplus to England's one-day requirements, hit 158, his first championship century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and led by 82 in the first innings.

By the end Yorkshire had turned this into a 37-run advantage, but off-spinner Such had dashed their hopes by taking four for 24 from 48 balls, leaving them hanging on for 119 from five and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man suspended by England, continued to silence his critics when, after four 45-point games on Thursday, he played an 80-point match against Warwickshire on Friday.
He was well supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who scored 70 points as Surrey closed the match on 429 points from seven for a 234-point lead.
Derbyshire continued their quest for a first title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 points from five in the second innings, and were still 100 runs away from avoiding defeat.
Australian Tom Moody scored 82 points from six games, but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, took Derbyshire to 471 points and a 233-point lead in the first innings.
After being frustrated by the weather, after the opening day of the match had gone badly wrong, Kent stepped up the pace and lost to Nottinghamshire by 214 points.
Paul Johnson's tenacious 84 kept them going, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague took four shots off 55.
By Stumps, Kent had scored 108 points out of three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER NAMED AS ENGLAND CAPTAIN.
Alan Shearer, the world's most expensive footballer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who moved to Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams, who led the team at the European Championship in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's opening World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer will take over the captaincy on trial, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton skipper should not take over.
"I'm sure there will be no problems, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," said Hoddle.
"Three or four people could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was ready for it and really wanted it.
"In four days it is very difficult to draw a 100% conclusion on such a matter...".
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows the team's situation even when he's playing up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 player Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the team on Friday due to injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.
FOOTBALL - ROMANIA BEAT LITHUANIA IN AN UNDER-21 MATCH.
Romania beat Lithuania 2-1 (1-1 at half-time) in an Under-21 European football match on Friday.
FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS LOCKED OUTSIDE AFTER VOLGOGRAD VIOLENCE.

Rotor Volgograd will have to play their next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 home defeat that ended Rotor's short season as league leaders.
Russian League Disciplinary Committee head Anatoly Gorokhovsky said on Friday that Rotor will play against Lada Togliatti on 3 September with empty stands.
The club that knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup was fined $1000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor are in a good position with 11 matches left in the championship series.
Volgograd, three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, have a one-match lead over the leaders and two over Moscow.
BOXING - ROBERTO DURAN FROM PANAMA FIGHTS AGAINST THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran will step into the ring on Saturday and once again defy age to continue his long career.
Duran, 45, will face little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in Panama City in a non-title super middleweight match.
The match, Duran's first in his home country for 10 years, is being billed here as the "return of the legend", and Duran still talks as if he were in his prime.
I am not retiring," Duran told Reuters.

However, it is recognised by those close to the boxer that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could undermine his status as one of the greatest boxers in the world," said Ramon Manzanares, president of the Panamanian Boxing Federation.
Duran, whose record of 97-12 spans three decades, hopes that a win in the 10 rounds would earn him a rematch against Puerto Rican Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho was awarded a controversial points decision against Panama City in a title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN SPRING DOUBLE DISASTER UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi avoided disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on the night of surprises at the U.S. Open.
The 11th-ranked Washington failed to repeat his miraculous return to Wimbledon when he lost to hot wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two-hour and 51-minute battle at the Stadium.
Rios, ranked 10th in the stands next to him, lost to another player with Wimbledon connections - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.

The day's programme went off without a hitch, although sixth-ranked former champion Agassi had to battle back from a dangerous 3-6 0-4 defeat after winning 18 of his last 19 games against Leander Paes of India.
But the night belonged to the upstarts.
Washington, who climbed back from a 1-5 deficit, two sets down in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals, looked poised for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title two weeks ago in New Haven, served for the match in the third set to go up 5-4 before Washington came back.
"I just said to myself: 'give yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen'," said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept my composure and was proud of myself for it - normally I would have folded up the tent and gone home."
The hard-serving O'Brien, a former US University champion, threw 17 aces and eventually defeated Washington, who never said "die".
The fifth set remained serve until the sixth game, when Washington saved a break point with a backhand shot, then netted a backhand shot to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan banged two aces to keep the service point at 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point for the win when Washington found the net with another backhand for a 40-0 lead.
"You just kind of keep fighting and trying to get him to play a little bit.
I think he was a little tense for a couple of moments," said Washington."
But I think he served pretty well when he had to. "

Tarango, whose Wimbledon tantrum two years ago earned him a $28 000 fine and a ban from this year's tournament at the All-England Club, argued over phone calls and taunted fans in a lively two-hour and 24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
The boisterous crowd supported the distracted Chilean and booed the slender American, who ate up all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, ranked 104th. "
I think I played very well today, very focused. "
The match came down to a tiebreak in the third set, which the American won 7-5 to the amazement of the crowd.
"I love the public, even if they boo me every day.
It gives me energy and makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I was playing my best tennis in college when the student unions were throwing beer at me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I think that's not the point.
I think I played really badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
The balls were moving really fast.
I lost too many points, which I never lose.
"I can't see the ball like I can during the day.
I play American, so that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango blew sarcastic kisses to the crowd and then waved his body in a mocking salute to the Rios supporters.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they are cheering loudly against me.
After I won, I thought I could give them a bit of a bash. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALLER RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leading quarterback at quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to play center field, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Cunningham ran for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I want to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful fans of Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I am sad to leave, I look forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles during his 11 years in Philadelphia and brought many great moments to Philadelphia and NFL fans. "
A second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham completed 1874-3362 passes (55.7 percent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already been awarded a contract as a broadcaster.
